user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 8.13.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 is A pointer should point to a const-qualified type whenever possible.

</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl.
```c
int32 OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl(const OS_object_token_t *token, OS_module_prop_t *module_prop)
{
    /*
     * Limiting strictly to POSIX-defined API means there is no defined
     * method to get information about a module contents.
     *
     * The "dlinfo()" function might return some interesting information
     * but this is actually a non-posix extension / platform-defined API.
     *
     * This returns success - although there is no information to add here,
     * the parent/shared layer information is still valid.
     */
    return OS_SUCCESS;
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The pointer 'module' is declared as 'OS_module_internal_record_t *module;' but in the shown code it is only used for read-only access (module->file_name is read and copied via strncpy). According to MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 it should be const-qualified when possible, e.g. 'const OS_module_internal_record_t *module;'. Therefore the declaration as a non-const pointer violates Rule 8.13 in this context.
</scenario>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are close to the target function OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl:
int32 OS_ModuleInfo(osal_id_t module_id, OS_module_prop_t *module_prop)
{
    OS_common_record_t *         record;
    OS_module_internal_record_t *module;
    int32                        return_code;
    OS_object_token_t            token;

    /* Check parameters */
    OS_CHECK_POINTER(module_prop);

    memset(module_prop, 0, sizeof(OS_module_prop_t));

    return_code = OS_ObjectIdGetById(OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE, module_id, &token);
    if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        record = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_global_module_table, token);
        module = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_module_table, token);

        strncpy(module_prop->name, record->name_entry, sizeof(module_prop->name) - 1);
        strncpy(module_prop->filename, module->file_name, sizeof(module_prop->filename) - 1);

        return_code = OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl(&token, module_prop);

        OS_ObjectIdRelease(&token);
    }

    return return_code;
}
</additional code>

<instruction>
Judge whether the report is correct or not.
</instruction>

explanation:
The agent A report is correct. In the provided OS_ModuleInfo code the local variable

    OS_module_internal_record_t *module;

is only used for read-only access (module->file_name is read and copied). According to MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 a pointer should point to a const-qualified type whenever possible, so the declaration should be

    const OS_module_internal_record_t *module;

Assigning the table lookup (which returns a non-const pointer) to a pointer-to-const is allowed and safe; there is no evidence in the shown code that the object is modified through module or passed to an API that requires a non-const pointer. Therefore the non-const declaration is a violation of Rule 8.13 in this context. (Note: the tiny OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl shown already uses a const token parameter; the problematic declaration occurs in OS_ModuleInfo in the additional code.)
